There are **two separate test failures**.

### 1. `getUserById()` still uses `WebClient`

The error says:

```text
Cannot invoke WebClient.RequestHeadersUriSpec.uri(...)
because the return value of webClient.get() is null
```

So `getUserById()` is not using `RestClient`; it still uses the existing `webClient`.

Keep both clients mocked:

```java
@Mock
private WebClient webClient;

@Mock
private WebClient.RequestHeadersUriSpec<?> webClientRequestUriSpec;

@Mock
private WebClient.RequestHeadersSpec<?> webClientRequestHeadersSpec;

@Mock
private WebClient.ResponseSpec webClientResponseSpec;

@Mock
private RestClient partnerRepoClient;
```

Use the WebClient chain for `shouldGetUserByIdSuccessfully()`:

```java
@Test
void shouldGetUserByIdSuccessfully() {
    UserResponse expectedResponse = new UserResponse();
    expectedResponse.setUserId("testuser");
    expectedResponse.setUsername("testuser");

    doReturn(webClientRequestUriSpec)
            .when(webClient)
            .get();

    doReturn(webClientRequestHeadersSpec)
            .when(webClientRequestUriSpec)
            .uri(
                    "http://partner-repository/users/{userId}",
                    "testuser"
            );

    when(webClientRequestHeadersSpec.retrieve())
            .thenReturn(webClientResponseSpec);

    when(webClientResponseSpec.bodyToMono(UserResponse.class))
            .thenReturn(Mono.just(expectedResponse));

    UserResponse result =
            partnerRepositoryClient.getUserById("testuser");

    assertEquals("testuser", result.getUserId());
    assertEquals("testuser", result.getUsername());
}
```

Required import:

```java
import reactor.core.publisher.Mono;
```

Your production class is therefore mixed at the moment:

```java
getApp(...)       -> RestClient
getUserById(...)  -> WebClient
```

So the tests must reflect that.

